        <article class="comment-article com-show" id="tree_47609643" data-cid="47609643">
    <div id="comment_47609643">
        <header data-points="3" data-reason="Insightful">
            <h3 class="comment-title" data-subject="Re: Correction: T-Mobile Android Smartphones"><i class="com-toggle fa fa-caret-down"></i>Re: Correction: T-Mobile Android Smartphones<span> (3, Insightful)</span></h3>
            <h4 class="avatar-tiny"><a href="//beta.slashdot.org/~Anubis+IV" class="author" title="author name and user ID">Anubis IV (1279820) </a> | about 2 months ago | <a href="//beta.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=5496249&cid=47609643">(#47609643)</a></h4>
        </header>
        <div id="comment_body_47609643" class="comment-wrapper" data-points="3" data-reason="Insightful">
            <div class="comment-body"><p>They were <a href="https://www.comscore.com/Insights/Market-Rankings/comScore-Reports-May-2014-U.S.-Smartphone-Subscriber-Market-Share" title="comscore.com">at 41% for the three-month period ending in May</a> <span class="domain-text"> [comscore.com]</span> . Two factors to keep in mind here: this research pertains specifically to US carriers, so it makes sense to look specifically at US market share, and we're specifically looking at smartphones, not the general cellular market. Globally, Apple's market share is significantly lower than in the US, even more so once you factor in non-smartphones, so I don't doubt that 15% is probably accurate somewhere for some set of conditions, but it isn't applicable in this particular case. 41% is the applicable number in this case.</p></div>
            <footer class="comment-footer" id="comment_footer_47609643">
